column69: Everglades National Park, south side of Bottle Key
column76: Miami-Dade County, Florida, United States
column153: On a red mangrove prop root. On the southern side of bottle key indicated by map. I tagged the tree that the iguanas were sunning on. it is flagged with one blue flag and one pink flag. pink flag says iguana. the tree with the iguana is in between 2 other blue flagged areas fairly close by (within 50 yards?). I saw 2 green iguanas sunning themselves in the prop roots of a mangrove on the southwest side of bottle key. One iguana was about 2 feet total, about1 foot long without tail. the other iguana was about 3.5 feet long total, 2 feet long without tail. both looking quite green but the smaller one was a brighter green. I believe I have pictures I may be able to find if need be, however there is no question in my mind that this was a green iguana. I only have pictures of the smaller on. both were quite obviously green iguanas.

column69: Everglades National Park, S side of Sandy Key
column76: Monroe County, Florida, United States
column153: Saw a large adult green iguana in bushes (some Brazilian Pepper) around old bird nests from last year. tried to get a picture but he bolted as soon as he could tell we saw him. Not too far from the beach. Probably around 3 pm, in the shade wind was around 10-15 but s/he was in a protected area. this is the second time this year that I have been to this key doing work on spoonbills and both times I have ran into an iguana looking similar to this. I could not get a picture either time but my co-worker (Michael Kline) and I both saw it this time and it was definitely a green iguana.

column153: A pair of 3 1/2 to 4 ft reptiles on the shoreline of a small "overflow" creek next to the high school I teach at. They were a dark green to brown color with embelishment on the crown of the head but none on the back or tail. They were long and lean, not thick in teh middle. I have owned and spent time with Monitors and believe that these may be monitors. Initially reported as Nile monitor. Larry Connor, FWCC, changed the species to Iguana iguana after Mathews identified the lizards from the Internet.

column153: First hatchling (approximately 16 grams) of 2013 breeding season. This individual was seen and captured on June 29 in rather unusual circumstances: 1. on the ground in road shoulder's relatively dense but 3-4" tall grass and 2. at 10PM. column153: 0.1 mi E of Kirby Storter trailhead parking lot in Big Cypress National Park, on the S side of the road near the bridge. roadkilled iguana with eggs (sterile). 2-3ft long brownish green iguana with wide bands along tail. Along its back, there was a stream of spikey spines. I have taken a photograph of this roadkill if needed for further identification (unfortunately I do not have the means to copy the photo from my camera, please e-mail me to remind me to send them to you). Also, I collected this specimen for Big Cypress National Preserve, where it is currently in a freezer. Please contact biologist Deb Jansen if you want to see the specimen at 239-340-0210.

column2: James Duquesnel Florida International University
column7: James Duquesnel Florida International University
column69: Approach to Old Bahia Honda Bridge, Bahia Honda State Park, 38650 Overseas Highway, Big Pine Key, FL 33043, USA
column76: Monroe County, Florida, United States
column153: Removed 200+ green iguanas (80% were sexually mature, and many females were gravid) from Bahia Honda Key between December 2010 and October 2011.  Iguana densities highest south and west of park entrance, especially on or near the fill placed to provide (pre-1929 Labor Day Hurricane) trains with gradual uphill grade for approach to historic Flagler Railroad bridge), though it is likely any iguanas in less used portions of park (esp. north of highway) are more wary and harder to census.  Higher densities here appear to result from combination of three factors: 1) proximity to primary parking area (where pet owners drop off unwanted iguanas), 2) filled bridge approach provides suitable substrate for burrows used as refuge from cold weather, and 3) habituation of iguanas to humans (tourists) who either do no look for/notice iguanas or, who if they do see iguanas, are almost always non-threatening. This last factor makes many of Bahia Honda's iguanas "naive" (easy to observe, approach closely, or even capture), at least in areas heavily used by park visitors.

column76: Martin County, Florida, United States
column153: The marina is surrounded with open fields and paved parking lots, lined with concrete bulkheads/seawalls, and currently in a state of disrepair. The seawall appears to be failing in several areas and the Iguanas have created numerous burrows throughout the areas adjacent to the seawall. During our site visit, we witnessed close to a dozen individuals basking throughout the marina. On approach, all of the Iguanas lept into the water and did not resurface within our field of vision. Burrows occured throughout the site, appeared to vary in size, and seemed to concentrate along the seawall.
